# Security Baseline

Security is a product requirement, not a nice-to-have.

## Always

- Validate **every** input via `class-validator` DTOs (global `ValidationPipe` already configured in `main.ts` with `whitelist + forbidNonWhitelisted + transform`)
- Enforce `JwtAuthGuard` + `RolesGuard` on every authenticated endpoint
- Use parameterized queries (Prisma ORM); raw SQL requires review
- Verify webhook signatures when provider supports it
- Implement idempotency on webhooks and payment-like operations
- Apply rate limiting via the project's own `rate-limiting/` module (NOT `@nestjs/throttler`) on auth-sensitive and AI endpoints
- Use strict CORS allowlist (no `*` in production) — configured in `main.ts` via `CORS_ORIGINS` env
- Paginate every list endpoint (no unbounded results)
- Log via `winston` + `nest-winston` (structured): request id, tenant id, actor id, event type, error code — never secrets
- Hash passwords with `argon2` (already installed; not bcrypt)
- Track metrics via `prom-client` (Prometheus); already installed

## Never

- ❌ Commit secrets (`.env`, keys, tokens) — use env vars + secret manager
- ❌ Trust frontend data (re-validate server-side)
- ❌ Trust `tenantId` from body when derivable from auth
- ❌ Concatenate user input into SQL strings
- ❌ Put API tokens in `localStorage` if cookies are an option
- ❌ Return raw Prisma entities with internal/sensitive fields
- ❌ Log: passwords, tokens, full API keys, CPF, raw AI prompts with PII
- ❌ Expose stack traces in production responses
- ❌ Create cross-tenant queries

## Examples

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
const user = await prisma.$queryRawUnsafe(`SELECT * FROM users WHERE email='${email}'`);

// ✅ GOOD
const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { email } });

// ✅ GOOD (raw with parameters when unavoidable)
const rows = await prisma.$queryRaw`SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = ${email}`;
```

```typescript
// ❌ BAD — leaks role/password hash
return user;

// ✅ GOOD — DTO with explicit fields
return { id: user.id, name: user.name, email: user.email };
```

## Dependency hygiene

Before merge: `pnpm audit`. Update vulnerable packages. Avoid abandoned packages.

